{"title_page": "Native Education College", "text_new": "{{Infobox university\n|name            = NEC Native Education College\n|native_name     =\n|latin_name      =\n|image           =\n|motto           = Your Journey Home\n|established     = 1967\n|type            = Private\n|endowment       =\n|staff           =\n|faculty         =\n|president       = [[Dan Guinan]]\n|chancellor      = Keith Henry \n|free_label      =\n|free            =\n|students        =\n|undergrad       =\n|city            = [[Vancouver]]\n|state           = [[British Columbia]]\n|country         = [[Canada]]\n|coor            = {{coord|49.2666|N|123.0993|W|region:CA-BC_type:edu|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|campus          = Urban\n|colours         =\n|mascot          =\n|nickname        =\n|affiliations    = Vancouver Community College\n|website         = {{URL|http://www.necvancouver.org/}}\n|logo            = Native Education Centre logo.png\n|logo_size       = 135px\n}}\n{{Indigenous Peoples of Canada}}\n\nThe '''NEC Native Education College''' is a registered private [[Aboriginal peoples in Canada|aboriginal]] [[college]] based in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]]. It is governed by non-profit society and is a registered [[charitable organization]].\n\n==Partnerships==\nNEC is a member of the Indigenous Adult and Higher Learning Association (IAHLA), which was created in 2003 to represent and work on behalf of Aboriginal controlled adult and post-secondary education institutes in British Columbia.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20111031130458/http://www.iahla.ca/ Indigenous Adult and Higher Learning Association]</ref>\n\n==Programs and courses==\nPrograms and courses offered include:\n\n* Aboriginal Adult Basic Education\n* Health Care Assistant\n* Aboriginal Tourism Operations\n* Aboriginal Tourism Management\n* Family and Community Counselling\n* [[Early Childhood Education]]\n* Aboriginal Justice Studies\n* Applied Business Technology\n* Northwest Coast Jewellery Arts\n\n==History==\nAlthough NEC (formerly Native Education Centre) had existed since 1967, it was in 1979 that the society was formed to assume control and broaden the scope of education to include academic post-secondary courses. The school moved into its current facilities in 1985, a building featuring architectural features of a traditional [[Native American long house|Pacific Coast longhouse]].\n\nThe Board of Directors of NEC Native Education Society made the decision to cease operations of NEC Native Education College effective July 31, 2007.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://firstnationsdrum.com/2007/07/native-education-centre%E2%80%99s-final-graduation-lack-of-funding-threatens-closure-of-b-c-%E2%80%99s-oldest-aboriginal-post-secondary-institution/|title=Native Education Centre\u2019s Final Graduation: Lack of Funding Threatens Closure of B.C.\u2019s oldest aboriginal Post-Secondary Institution|last=Dolha|first=Lloyd|date=July 2007|work=First Nations Drum|accessdate=28 January 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120710050256/http://firstnationsdrum.com/2007/07/native-education-centre%E2%80%99s-final-graduation-lack-of-funding-threatens-closure-of-b-c-%E2%80%99s-oldest-aboriginal-post-secondary-institution/|archivedate=10 July 2012}}</ref> This decision was overturned in late July with support of the Ministry of Advanced Education to develop a new funding formula for private Aboriginal colleges in late 2007.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Mirehouse, V. Grace. \"The Native Education Centre: its impact on cultural identity and educational outcomes.\" Master of Arts, [[University of British Columbia]].\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.necvancouver.org/}}\n\n{{BC Uni|private=yes|college=yes}}\n{{North American Tribal Colleges and Universities}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1967]]\n[[Category:First Nations education]]\n[[Category:Indigenous universities and colleges in North America]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Vancouver]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox university\n|name            = NEC Native Education College\n|native_name     =\n|latin_name      =\n|image           =\n|motto           = Your Journey Home\n|established     = 1967\n|type            = Private\n|endowment       =\n|staff           =\n|faculty         =\n|president       = [[Dan Guinan]]\n|chancellor      = Keith Henry \n|free_label      =\n|free            =\n|students        =\n|undergrad       =\n|city            = [[Vancouver]]\n|state           = [[British Columbia]]\n|country         = [[Canada]]\n|coor            = {{coord|49.2666|N|123.0993|W|region:CA-BC_type:edu|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|campus          = Urban\n|colours         =\n|mascot          =\n|nickname        =\n|affiliations    = Vancouver Community College\n|website         = {{URL|http://www.necvancouver.org/}}\n|logo            = Native Education Centre logo.png\n|logo_size       = 135px\n}}\n{{Indigenous Peoples of Canada}}\n\nThe '''NEC Native Education College''' is a registered private [[Aboriginal peoples in Canada|aboriginal]] [[college]] based in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]]. It is governed by non-profit society and is a registered [[charitable organization]].\n\n==Partnerships==\nNEC is a member of the Indigenous Adult and Higher Learning Association (IAHLA), which was created in 2003 to represent and work on behalf of Aboriginal controlled adult and post-secondary education institutes in British Columbia.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20111031130458/http://www.iahla.ca/ Indigenous Adult and Higher Learning Association]</ref>\n\n==Programs and courses==\nPrograms and courses offered include:\n\n* Aboriginal Adult Basic Education\n* Health Care Assistant\n* Aboriginal Tourism Operations\n* Aboriginal Tourism Management\n* Family and Community Counselling\n* [[Early Childhood Education]]\n* Aboriginal Justice Studies\n* Applied Business Technology\n* Northwest Coast Jewellery Arts\n\n==History==\nAlthough NEC (formerly Native Education Centre) had existed since 1967, it was in 1979 that the society was formed to assume control and broaden the scope of education to include academic post-secondary courses. The school moved into its current facilities in 1985, a building featuring architectural features of a traditional [[Native American long house|Pacific Coast longhouse]].\n\nThe Board of Directors of NEC Native Education Society made the decision to cease operations of NEC Native Education College effective July 31, 2007.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://firstnationsdrum.com/2007/07/native-education-centre%E2%80%99s-final-graduation-lack-of-funding-threatens-closure-of-b-c-%E2%80%99s-oldest-aboriginal-post-secondary-institution/|title=Native Education Centre\u2019s Final Graduation: Lack of Funding Threatens Closure of B.C.\u2019s oldest aboriginal Post-Secondary Institution|last=Dolha|first=Lloyd|date=July 2007|work=First Nations Drum|accessdate=28 January 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120710050256/http://firstnationsdrum.com/2007/07/native-education-centre%E2%80%99s-final-graduation-lack-of-funding-threatens-closure-of-b-c-%E2%80%99s-oldest-aboriginal-post-secondary-institution/|archivedate=10 July 2012}}</ref> This decision was overturned in late July with support of the Ministry of Advanced Education to develop a new funding formula for private Aboriginal colleges in late 2007.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Mirehouse, V. Grace. \"The Native Education Centre: its impact on cultural identity and educational outcomes.\" Master of Arts, [[University of British Columbia]].\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.necvancouver.org/}}\n\n{{BC Uni|private=yes|college=yes}}\n{{North American Tribal Colleges and Universities}}\n\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1967]]\n[[Category:First Nations education]]\n[[Category:Indigenous universities and colleges in North America]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Vancouver]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Native_Education_College"}
